One year ago, the words came on the roar of the monsoon wind. Fire in Yarnell; nineteen lost. The Granite Mountain Hotshots. 

Arizona gathered, friends and strangers side by side. Along the roadsides for a somber procession. Outside a solemn memorial where a bell rang 19 times.

The gifts came quietly at first, a single flag tucked amid the diamonds of a chain-link fence. On that fence, outside the hotshots' station house, a memorial grew and grew with memories poured out, tributes shared. 

Today, the bells will ring again. And when they fade into silence, 19 memories will remain. 

Watch live coverage here --> http://azc.cc/1mqK6e1

A day to remember: It was one year ago Monday that 19 Granite Mountain Hotshots lost their lives fighting to protect Arizona communities from the Yarnell Hill Fire. Find a special tribute to these brave men in Monday's Arizona Republic.

In honor of Mother's Day, we want to create a video that celebrates Arizona moms, but we need your help. Send us a short 3-to-5 second video that celebrates your mom, saying or showing — why your mom is wonderful.
Here are some ideas:
-Show your favorite dinner that Mom makes.
-Give us a quick tour of the best part of your mother's garden.
-Does your mom give great hugs? Videotape her giving you a hug.
-Gather your whole family to shout, "Happy Mother's Day!"
-Take a video selfie of you and your mom laughing.
E-mail your video to dave.seibert@arizonarepublic.com. We can take any format; just keep it under 25 megabytes in size. Include a short message with your first and last name and your mother's name, along with your city/cities of residence. 
And go give your mom a hug!

status_message: UPDATE: Rescue operations continue at Chile mine. It could take as long as 36 hours for all 33 miners to be brought to the surface in the capsule, named Phoenix for the mythical bird that rises from ashes.

UPDATE: Second miner, Mario Sepulveda, lifted to the surface safely. The 1st man to be rescued was chosen because he was thought most likely to be able to handle any difficulties during the ascent. The weaker and ill miners will be next. The last man will be shift foreman Luis Urzua, whose leadership was credited with helping the men endure their time underground.
BREAKING NEWS: First miner rescued. Florencio Avalos is the first miner to be lifted above ground in the capsule.
WATCH IT LIVE: 33 miners who have been trapped underground longer than anyone in history are edging closer to freedom and fresh air as the rescue attempt in Chile is underway.
link_name: Miners' endurance and unity have captivated the world
